events.description: Publius Valerius Publicola celebrates the first triumph of the Roman Republic after his victory over the deposed king Lucius Tarquinius Superbus at the Battle of Silva Arsia.
events.html: • 509 BC – Publius Valerius Publicola celebrates the first triumph of the Roman Republic after his victory over the deposed king Lucius Tarquinius Superbus at the Battle of Silva Arsia.[1]

events.description: Emperor Diocletian and Maximian appoint Constantius Chlorus and Galerius as Caesars. This is considered the beginning of the Tetrarchy, known as the Quattuor Principes Mundi ("Four Rulers of the World").
events.html: • 293 – Emperor Diocletian and Maximian appoint Constantius Chlorus and Galerius as Caesars. This is considered the beginning of the Tetrarchy, known as the Quattuor Principes Mundi ("Four Rulers of the World").[2]

events.description: Vetranio proclaims himself Caesar after being encouraged to do so by Constantina, sister of Constantius II.
events.html: • 350 – Vetranio proclaims himself Caesar after being encouraged to do so by Constantina, sister of Constantius II.[3]

events.description: Emperor Louis the Pious is restored as sole ruler of the Frankish Empire.
events.html: • 834 – Emperor Louis the Pious is restored as sole ruler of the Frankish Empire.[4]

events.description: Forces of the Catholic Monarchs engage the combined Portuguese-Castilian armies of Afonso V and Prince John at the Battle of Toro.
events.html: • 1476 – Forces of the Catholic Monarchs engage the combined Portuguese-Castilian armies of Afonso V and Prince John at the Battle of Toro.[5]

events.description: Sixty-three Huguenots are massacred in Wassy, France, marking the start of the French Wars of Religion.
events.html: • 1562 – Sixty-three Huguenots are massacred in Wassy, France, marking the start of the French Wars of Religion.[6]

events.description: Writs issued in February by Charles I of England mandate that every county in England (not just seaport towns) pay ship tax by this date.
events.html: • 1628 – Writs issued in February by Charles I of England mandate that every county in England (not just seaport towns) pay ship tax by this date.

events.description: Samuel de Champlain reclaims his role as commander of New France on behalf of Cardinal Richelieu.
events.html: • 1633 – Samuel de Champlain reclaims his role as commander of New France on behalf of Cardinal Richelieu.

events.description: Sarah Good, Sarah Osborne and Tituba are brought before local magistrates in Salem Village, Massachusetts, beginning what would become known as the Salem witch trials.
events.html: • 1692 – Sarah Good, Sarah Osborne and Tituba are brought before local magistrates in Salem Village, Massachusetts, beginning what would become known as the Salem witch trials.

events.description: The Articles of Confederation goes into effect in the United States.
events.html: • 1781 – The Articles of Confederation goes into effect in the United States.[7]

events.description: The Dutch East India Company is nationalized by the Batavian Republic.
events.html: • 1796 – The Dutch East India Company is nationalized by the Batavian Republic.

events.description: Justice Samuel Chase is acquitted at the end of his impeachment trial by the U.S. Senate.
events.html: • 1805 – Justice Samuel Chase is acquitted at the end of his impeachment trial by the U.S. Senate.[8]

events.description: Leaders of the Mamluk dynasty are killed by Egyptian ruler Muhammad Ali.
events.html: • 1811 – Leaders of the Mamluk dynasty are killed by Egyptian ruler Muhammad Ali.

events.description: Napoleon returns to France from his banishment on Elba.
events.html: • 1815 – Napoleon returns to France from his banishment on Elba.

events.description: A convention of delegates from 57 Texas communities convenes in Washington-on-the-Brazos, Texas, to deliberate independence from Mexico.
events.html: • 1836 – A convention of delegates from 57 Texas communities convenes in Washington-on-the-Brazos, Texas, to deliberate independence from Mexico.

events.description: United States President John Tyler signs a bill authorizing the United States to annex the Republic of Texas.
events.html: • 1845 – United States President John Tyler signs a bill authorizing the United States to annex the Republic of Texas.

events.description: Nebraska is admitted as the 37th U.S. state.
events.html: • 1867 – Nebraska is admitted as the 37th U.S. state.

events.description: Marshal F. S. López dies during the Battle of Cerro Corá thus marking the end of the Paraguayan War.
events.html: • 1870 – Marshal F. S. López dies during the Battle of Cerro Corá thus marking the end of the Paraguayan War.

events.description: The victorious Prussian Army parades through Paris, France, after the end of the Siege of Paris during the Franco-Prussian War.
events.html: • 1871 – The victorious Prussian Army parades through Paris, France, after the end of the Siege of Paris during the Franco-Prussian War.[9]

events.description: Yellowstone National Park is established as the world's first national park.
events.html: • 1872 – Yellowstone National Park is established as the world's first national park.

events.description: Electrical engineer Nikola Tesla gives the first public demonstration of radio in St. Louis, Missouri.
events.html: • 1893 – Electrical engineer Nikola Tesla gives the first public demonstration of radio in St. Louis, Missouri.

events.description: Battle of Adwa: An Ethiopian army defeats an outnumbered Italian force, ending the First Italo-Ethiopian War.
events.html: • 1896 – Battle of Adwa: An Ethiopian army defeats an outnumbered Italian force, ending the First Italo-Ethiopian War.[10]

events.description: Henri Becquerel discovers radioactive decay.
events.html: • 1896 – Henri Becquerel discovers radioactive decay.

events.description: The Australian Army is formed.
events.html: • 1901 – The Australian Army is formed.

events.description: The deadliest avalanche in United States history buries a Great Northern Railway train in northeastern King County, Washington, killing 96 people.
events.html: • 1910 – The deadliest avalanche in United States history buries a Great Northern Railway train in northeastern King County, Washington, killing 96 people.

events.description: China joins the Universal Postal Union.
events.html: • 1914 – China joins the Universal Postal Union.

events.description: The Zimmermann Telegram is reprinted in newspapers across the United States after the U.S. government releases its unencrypted text.
events.html: • 1917 – The Zimmermann Telegram is reprinted in newspapers across the United States after the U.S. government releases its unencrypted text.

entities.name: Federal government of the United States

events.description: March 1st Movement begins in Korea under Japanese rule.
events.html: • 1919 – March 1st Movement begins in Korea under Japanese rule.

events.description: The Australian cricket team captained by Warwick Armstrong becomes the first team to complete a whitewash of The Ashes, something that would not be repeated for 86 years.
events.html: • 1921 – The Australian cricket team captained by Warwick Armstrong becomes the first team to complete a whitewash of The Ashes, something that would not be repeated for 86 years.

events.description: Following mass protests in Petrograd demanding greater freedom in the RSFSR, the Kronstadt rebellion begins, with sailors and citizens taking up arms against the Bolsheviks.
events.html: • 1921 – Following mass protests in Petrograd demanding greater freedom in the RSFSR, the Kronstadt rebellion begins, with sailors and citizens taking up arms against the Bolsheviks.[11]

events.description: Aviator Charles Lindbergh's 20-month-old son Charles Jr is kidnapped from his home in East Amwell, New Jersey. His body would not be found until May 12.
events.html: • 1932 – Aviator Charles Lindbergh's 20-month-old son Charles Jr is kidnapped from his home in East Amwell, New Jersey. His body would not be found until May 12.[12]

events.description: An Imperial Japanese Army ammunition dump explodes at Hirakata, Osaka, Japan, killing 94.
events.html: • 1939 – An Imperial Japanese Army ammunition dump explodes at Hirakata, Osaka, Japan, killing 94.

events.description: World War II: Bulgaria signs the Tripartite Pact, allying itself with the Axis powers.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: Bulgaria signs the Tripartite Pact, allying itself with the Axis powers.

events.description: World War II: Japanese forces land on Java, the main island of the Dutch East Indies, at Merak and Banten Bay (Banten), Eretan Wetan (Indramayu) and Kragan (Rembang).
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Japanese forces land on Java, the main island of the Dutch East Indies, at Merak and Banten Bay (Banten), Eretan Wetan (Indramayu) and Kragan (Rembang).

events.description: The Bank of England is nationalised.
events.html: • 1946 – The Bank of England is nationalised.

events.description: The International Monetary Fund begins financial operations.
events.html: • 1947 – The International Monetary Fund begins financial operations.

events.description: Cold War: Klaus Fuchs is convicted of spying for the Soviet Union by disclosing top secret atomic bomb data.
events.html: • 1950 – Cold War: Klaus Fuchs is convicted of spying for the Soviet Union by disclosing top secret atomic bomb data.

events.description: Soviet Premier Joseph Stalin suffers a stroke and collapses; he dies four days later.
events.html: • 1953 – Soviet Premier Joseph Stalin suffers a stroke and collapses; he dies four days later.

events.description: Nuclear weapons testing: The Castle Bravo, a 15-megaton hydrogen bomb, is detonated on Bikini Atoll in the Pacific Ocean, resulting in the worst radioactive contamination ever caused by the United States.
events.html: • 1954 – Nuclear weapons testing: The Castle Bravo, a 15-megaton hydrogen bomb, is detonated on Bikini Atoll in the Pacific Ocean, resulting in the worst radioactive contamination ever caused by the United States.

events.description: Armed Puerto Rican nationalists attack the United States Capitol building, injuring five Representatives.
events.html: • 1954 – Armed Puerto Rican nationalists attack the United States Capitol building, injuring five Representatives.

events.description: The International Air Transport Association finalizes a draft of the Radiotelephony spelling alphabet for the International Civil Aviation Organization.
events.html: • 1956 – The International Air Transport Association finalizes a draft of the Radiotelephony spelling alphabet for the International Civil Aviation Organization.

events.description: Formation of the East German Nationale Volksarmee.
events.html: • 1956 – Formation of the East German Nationale Volksarmee.

events.description: Samuel Alphonsus Stritch is appointed Pro-Prefect of the Propagation of Faith and thus becomes the first U.S. member of the Roman Curia.
events.html: • 1958 – Samuel Alphonsus Stritch is appointed Pro-Prefect of the Propagation of Faith and thus becomes the first U.S. member of the Roman Curia.

events.description: Uganda becomes self-governing and holds its first elections.
events.html: • 1961 – Uganda becomes self-governing and holds its first elections.

events.description: American Airlines Flight 1 crashes into Jamaica Bay in New York, killing 95.
events.html: • 1962 – American Airlines Flight 1 crashes into Jamaica Bay in New York, killing 95.[13]

events.description: Villarrica Volcano begins a strombolian eruption causing lahars that destroy half of the town of Coñaripe.
events.html: • 1964 – Villarrica Volcano begins a strombolian eruption causing lahars that destroy half of the town of Coñaripe.

events.description: Paradise Airlines Flight 901A crashes near Lake Tahoe, Nevada, killing 85.
events.html: • 1964 – Paradise Airlines Flight 901A crashes near Lake Tahoe, Nevada, killing 85.[14]

events.description: Venera 3 Soviet space probe crashes on Venus becoming the first spacecraft to land on another planet's surface.
events.html: • 1966 – Venera 3 Soviet space probe crashes on Venus becoming the first spacecraft to land on another planet's surface.

events.description: The Ba'ath Party takes power in Syria.
events.html: • 1966 – The Ba'ath Party takes power in Syria.

events.description: President of Pakistan Yahya Khan indefinitely postpones the pending national assembly session, precipitating massive civil disobedience in East Pakistan.
events.html: • 1971 – President of Pakistan Yahya Khan indefinitely postpones the pending national assembly session, precipitating massive civil disobedience in East Pakistan.

events.description: Black September storms the Saudi embassy in Khartoum, Sudan, resulting in the assassination of three Western hostages.
events.html: • 1973 – Black September storms the Saudi embassy in Khartoum, Sudan, resulting in the assassination of three Western hostages.

entities.name: Attack on the Saudi Embassy in Khartoum

events.description: Watergate scandal: Seven are indicted for their role in the Watergate break-in and charged with conspiracy to obstruct justice.
events.html: • 1974 – Watergate scandal: Seven are indicted for their role in the Watergate break-in and charged with conspiracy to obstruct justice.

events.description: Provisional Irish Republican Army member Bobby Sands begins his hunger strike in HM Prison Maze.
events.html: • 1981 – Provisional Irish Republican Army member Bobby Sands begins his hunger strike in HM Prison Maze.

events.description: Steve Jackson Games is raided by the United States Secret Service, prompting the later formation of the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
events.html: • 1990 – Steve Jackson Games is raided by the United States Secret Service, prompting the later formation of the Electronic Frontier Foundation.

events.description: Uprisings against Saddam Hussein begin in Iraq, leading to the deaths of more than 25,000 people, mostly civilians.
events.html: • 1991 – Uprisings against Saddam Hussein begin in Iraq, leading to the deaths of more than 25,000 people, mostly civilians.

events.description: Bosnia and Herzegovina declares its independence from Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
events.html: • 1992 – Bosnia and Herzegovina declares its independence from Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.

events.description: Titanic became the first film to gross over $1 billion worldwide.
events.html: • 1998 – Titanic became the first film to gross over $1 billion worldwide.

events.description: U.S. invasion of Afghanistan: Operation Anaconda begins in eastern Afghanistan.
events.html: • 2002 – U.S. invasion of Afghanistan: Operation Anaconda begins in eastern Afghanistan.

events.description: The Envisat environmental satellite successfully launches aboard an Ariane 5 rocket to reach an orbit of 800 km (500 mi) above the Earth, which was the then-largest payload at 10.5 m long and with a diameter of 4.57 m.
events.html: • 2002 – The Envisat environmental satellite successfully launches aboard an Ariane 5 rocket to reach an orbit of 800 km (500 mi) above the Earth, which was the then-largest payload at 10.5 m long and with a diameter of 4.57 m.[15]

events.description: Space Shuttle Columbia is launched on STS-109 to service the Hubble Space Telescope.
events.html: • 2002 – Space Shuttle Columbia is launched on STS-109 to service the Hubble Space Telescope.[16]

events.description: Management of the United States Customs Service and the United States Secret Service move to the United States Department of Homeland Security.
events.html: • 2003 – Management of the United States Customs Service and the United States Secret Service move to the United States Department of Homeland Security.

entities.name: United States Department of Homeland Security

events.description: In Roper v. Simmons, the U.S. Supreme Court rules that the execution of juveniles found guilty of any crime is unconstitutional.
events.html: • 2005 – In Roper v. Simmons, the U.S. Supreme Court rules that the execution of juveniles found guilty of any crime is unconstitutional.[17]

entities.name: Supreme Court of the United States

events.description: English-language Wikipedia reaches its one millionth article, Jordanhill railway station.
events.html: • 2006 – English-language Wikipedia reaches its one millionth article, Jordanhill railway station.[18]

events.description: Tornadoes break out across the southern United States, killing at least 20 people, including eight at Enterprise High School.
events.html: • 2007 – Tornadoes break out across the southern United States, killing at least 20 people, including eight at Enterprise High School.

events.description: The Armenian police clash with peaceful opposition rally protesting against allegedly fraudulent presidential elections, as a result ten people are killed.
events.html: • 2008 – The Armenian police clash with peaceful opposition rally protesting against allegedly fraudulent presidential elections, as a result ten people are killed.

events.description: Thirty-five people are killed and 143 injured in a mass stabbing at Kunming Railway Station in China.
events.html: • 2014 – Thirty-five people are killed and 143 injured in a mass stabbing at Kunming Railway Station in China.
